{
  "$type": "Models.Core.Simulations, Models",
  "Version": 192,
  "Name": "Simulations",
  "ResourceName": null,
  "Children": [
    {
      "$type": "Models.Memo, Models",
      "Text": "### Base simulation for calculating transport risk across New Zealand\n\n_Rogerio Cichota, Plant and Food Research, New Zealand_ and _Val Snow, AgResearch, New Zealand_\n\n\n_7 April 2025 - updated to r7717, simplified the factor structure and the reporting, and added in reporting of runoff at 30, 60 and 90 days_\n\nSee:\nSnow, V., R. Cichota, L. Lilburne, R. McDowell and S. Vickers (2024). \"A method to derive nitrogen transport factors for New Zealand's agricultural lands.\" MethodsX 13: 102814.\n\n\nInitially developed for the Whitiwhiti Ora / Land use opportunities programme, funded by Our Land and Water National Science Challenge, in \npartnership with the Risk Index Tool team from the New Zealand Ministry for the Environment.\n\nThis simulation contain the basic setup for simulating the fate of N from a spike of N applied to a mixed-species pasture sward.  \nIt is intended to be used as the template for a series of simulation runs on a HPC to obtain N leaching and runoff values that are then post-processed to calculate transport factors.  \nFor each run on the HPC, the template will be modified by replacing the soil node and the link to the weather data file to cover all farming areas of New Zealand.  \n\nThe simulation uses standard APSIM models. In particular, the AGPRyegrass and AGPWhiteClover models are used to simulate a mixed sward with variable clover content.  \nThe pasture is managed mimicking rotational grazing, with defoliations triggered by rules based on aboveground biomass with some restrictions for the interval between defoliations.  \nA simplified approach is used to return dung and for urine depositions.  Based on its digestibility, a certain fraction (around 20%) of the biomass harvested (i.e. of its carbon) is returned to the soil homogeneously as dung; a C:N ratio of 17.5 is used to define the amount of N returned as dung.  \nNo urine depositions are considered after each grazing to reduce its potential impact on the fate of N leaching.  \n\nThe weather data comes from the virtual climate station network (VCSN) of NIWA.  \nSoil information is provided by Manaaki Whenua - Landcare based on Smap.  \nGeneral rules are also used to control irrigation applications, when this management is enabled.  N fertiliser is not considered.  \nA single appication of nitrate-N is set to occur five months after the simulation begins and only outputs after this application date are considered.  \n\nNOTE: Most of the year-month combinations are disabled for speed of running within the test system\n",
      "Name": "TitlePage",
      "ResourceName": null,
      "Children": [],
      "Enabled": true,
      "ReadOnly": false
    },
